---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Artwork"
  description="Visual explorations of the Structural Regulation Framework — diagrams, models, and conceptual art."
>
  <article class="artwork-page">
    <header class="artwork-header">
      <p class="eyebrow">Visual Thinking</p>
      <h1>Artwork</h1>
      <p class="lead">
        Conceptual diagrams and visual models exploring the Structural Regulation Framework.
        Each piece is accompanied by a detailed explanation of what it represents.
      </p>
    </header>

    <section class="piece">
      <div class="piece-image">
        <img
          src="/artwork/electrical-circuit-model.png"
          alt="SRF Electrical Circuit Model — psychological regulation mapped as an electrical circuit with capacitor (IRC), inductor (REL), leakage resistor (SF), and threshold switch leading to externalization output via ORBIT vectors"
          loading="lazy"
        />
      </div>

      <div class="piece-text">
        <h2>SRF Electrical Circuit Model</h2>
        <p class="piece-subtitle">Psychological Regulation as an Electrical Circuit</p>

        <h3>What this diagram shows</h3>
        <p>
          The Structural Regulation Framework reimagined as an electrical circuit.
          Each component of the framework maps to a circuit element, and the flow
          of emotional activation through the system follows the logic of voltage,
          capacitance, and discharge.
        </p>

        <h3>Component mapping</h3>

        <div class="component">
          <h4>Activation Input (Voltage Source)</h4>
          <p>
            Emotional activation enters the system as voltage — generated by internal
            states or external events. This is the fundamental energy that the system
            must regulate. Every trigger, every relational event, every moment of
            uncertainty creates voltage in the circuit.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="component">
          <h4>ERD — Dependency Load (Resistor)</h4>
          <p>
            External Regulation Dependence functions as a load resistor that increases
            system sensitivity. Higher dependency means the same event creates more
            effective pressure in the system. A person with high ERD experiences the
            same ambiguous text message as a much larger voltage spike than someone
            with low ERD.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="component">
          <h4>IRC — Internal Regulation Capacity (Capacitor)</h4>
          <p>
            The capacitor stores and holds activation energy internally. Higher IRC
            means larger capacitance — more energy can be stored before the system
            reaches its threshold. This is the holding capacity: how much unresolved
            tension can the system contain without discharging externally.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="component">
          <h4>REL — Regulatory Latency (Inductor)</h4>
          <p>
            The inductor introduces delay before current flows. It resists sudden
            changes in current — creating the time interval between activation and
            behavioral response. This is REL: the temporal gap before externalization
            begins. The inductor allows time for internal processing or, if too long,
            for dangerous pressure buildup.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="component">
          <h4>SF — Structural Flexibility (Leakage Resistor)</h4>
          <p>
            A parallel discharge path that allows activation to dissipate internally
            through integration and processing. Higher SF means more leakage — more
            energy is safely processed without ever reaching the threshold switch.
            This is the internal processing pathway: tension transformed rather than
            expelled.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="component">
          <h4>Threshold Switch (Voltage Gate)</h4>
          <p>
            When activation voltage exceeds the system's capacity, the switch opens
            and energy discharges externally. This is the collapse point — the moment
            when internal regulation fails and externalization becomes inevitable.
            Not a choice. Circuit mechanics.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="component">
          <h4>Externalization Output (Current via ORBIT Vectors)</h4>
          <p>
            Once the threshold is exceeded, activation flows outward through specific
            channels: validation-seeking, dominance, attack, withdrawal, idealization,
            rescue, or control. These are the directions externalization takes — not
            random, but determined by the individual's habitual vector profile.
          </p>
        </div>

        <h3>System states</h3>
        <div class="states">
          <div class="state">
            <strong>Regulated</strong>
            <span>Voltage below threshold. Energy processed internally.</span>
          </div>
          <div class="state">
            <strong>Unstable</strong>
            <span>Voltage rising. Capacitor near full. Risk increasing.</span>
          </div>
          <div class="state">
            <strong>Collapse</strong>
            <span>Threshold exceeded. Switch opens. Externalization occurs.</span>
          </div>
          <div class="state">
            <strong>Recovery</strong>
            <span>After discharge. System resets. Circuit recalibrates.</span>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h3>Key insight</h3>
        <p class="insight">
          Externalization is not random — it is circuit mechanics. When the system
          cannot hold more voltage, it discharges. The direction of discharge (which
          vector) and the speed of discharge (REL) are structural properties of the
          circuit, not moral failures of the person.
        </p>

        <h3>Where the analogy breaks</h3>
        <p>
          No analogy is perfect. In a real circuit, a resistor reduces voltage — but
          ERD increases effective sensitivity. SF as a leakage resistor dissipates
          energy as heat — but real structural flexibility transforms tension into
          something useful rather than merely dissipating it. The threshold switch is
          binary — but real externalization is often gradual. These are pedagogical
          simplifications, not precise formalizations.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>
    <section class="piece">
      <div class="piece-image">
        <img
          src="/artwork/binary-world.png"
          alt="Black and white silhouette scene — people in a park rendered entirely without grey tones, representing the splitting mechanism where experience is compressed into all-good or all-bad without integration"
          loading="lazy"
        />
      </div>

      <div class="piece-text">
        <h2>The Binary World</h2>
        <p class="piece-subtitle">Splitting as a Compression Algorithm</p>

        <h3>What this image shows</h3>
        <p>
          A world rendered entirely in black and white. No grey. People, trees,
          buildings, relationships — all compressed into two values. Not because
          the world is actually binary, but because the system viewing it cannot
          hold both simultaneously.
        </p>

        <h3>The structural logic of splitting</h3>
        <p>
          This image works because it makes an abstract psychological mechanism
          immediately intuitive. The idea is not that someone literally sees people
          as black or white — but that experiential classification operates this way:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>Completely good</li>
          <li>Completely bad</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Without the stable capacity to hold in mind:
          <em>"This person hurt me AND can still be important to me"</em> — or —
          <em>"This person is mostly good, even though I'm disappointed right now."</em>
        </p>

        <h3>What is missing from this picture</h3>
        <p>
          Grey. The capacity to hold contradiction. The ability to experience
          someone as both disappointing and valuable at the same time without
          one canceling the other.
        </p>
        <p>
          In SRF terms: low structural flexibility + low contradiction tolerance
          under attachment activation → binary stabilization strategy.
        </p>

        <h3>Why the world becomes binary</h3>
        <p>
          The world is not black and white because the person wants to see it
          that way. It becomes binary because the system needs a rapid stabilization
          solution under contradiction. When the system cannot hold "good AND bad"
          simultaneously, it must choose one — and eliminate the other.
        </p>
        <div class="component">
          <h4>Idealization</h4>
          <p>Contradiction eliminated in the positive direction. All white. The object becomes entirely good, safe, perfect — because ambiguity is intolerable.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="component">
          <h4>Devaluation</h4>
          <p>Contradiction eliminated in the negative direction. All black. The object becomes entirely bad, worthless, threatening — because holding both would destabilize the system.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="component">
          <h4>The split itself</h4>
          <p>Not a personality flaw. A compression algorithm for an unstable system. Binary encoding is how the system preserves coherence when it cannot afford complexity.</p>
        </div>

        <h3>Integration as the first grey pixel</h3>
        <p>
          The beginning of integration is not a grand insight. It is the first
          moment where both can coexist without one destroying the other.
          The first grey pixel in a binary image. The experience:
          <em>"This person disappointed me — and I am still here. They are still here.
          We survived the contradiction."</em>
        </p>
        <p>
          That experience, repeated, builds contradiction holding capacity.
          The image gradually gains grey tones. Not because someone decided
          to "think more nuanced thoughts" — but because the system's capacity
          to hold complexity increased through survived experience.
        </p>

        <h3>The structural interpretation</h3>
        <p class="insight">
          Splitting is not a moral failure. It is what happens when a system
          that cannot hold contradiction encounters contradiction. The binary
          world is not chosen — it is the only world available when grey
          requires more structural flexibility than the system currently possesses.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

  </article>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .artwork-page {
    max-width: 900px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 2rem 0 4rem;
  }

  .artwork-header {
    margin-bottom: 3rem;
  }

  .eyebrow {
    margin: 0 0 0.75rem;
    font-size: 0.8rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.12em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--muted);
  }

  h1 {
    margin: 0 0 1rem;
    font-size: clamp(2.2rem, 5vw, 3.5rem);
    letter-spacing: -0.03em;
  }

  .lead {
    font-size: 1.1rem;
    line-height: 1.75;
    color: var(--muted);
  }

  .piece {
    margin-top: 2rem;
  }

  .piece-image {
    margin-bottom: 2.5rem;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: var(--radius);
    overflow: hidden;
    background: #fff;
  }

  .piece-image img {
    width: 100%;
    height: auto;
    display: block;
  }

  .piece-text h2 {
    margin: 0 0 0.25rem;
    font-size: 1.8rem;
    letter-spacing: -0.02em;
  }

  .piece-subtitle {
    margin: 0 0 2rem;
    font-size: 1.05rem;
    color: var(--muted);
    font-style: italic;
  }

  h3 {
    margin: 2rem 0 0.75rem;
    font-size: 1.2rem;
    letter-spacing: -0.01em;
  }

  h4 {
    margin: 0 0 0.4rem;
    font-size: 1rem;
    color: var(--accent);
  }

  p {
    line-height: 1.75;
    color: var(--muted);
  }

  ul {
    padding-left: 1.25rem;
    color: var(--muted);
    line-height: 1.75;
  }

  li {
    margin-bottom: 0.3rem;
  }

  .component {
    margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
    padding: 1.25rem;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: var(--radius);
    background: var(--surface);
  }

  .component p {
    margin: 0;
  }

  .states {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr);
    gap: 0.75rem;
    margin: 1rem 0;
  }

  .state {
    padding: 1rem;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: var(--radius);
    background: var(--surface);
  }

  .state strong {
    display: block;
    margin-bottom: 0.3rem;
    color: var(--text);
    font-size: 0.9rem;
  }

  .state span {
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    color: var(--muted);
    line-height: 1.5;
  }

  .insight {
    padding: 1.25rem;
    border-left: 3px solid var(--accent);
    background: var(--surface);
    border-radius: 0 var(--radius) var(--radius) 0;
    color: var(--text);
    font-size: 1.05rem;
  }

  @media (max-width: 640px) {
    .states {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }
  }
</style>
